            <h3>Loops</h3>
            <p>Loops in Java are control structures that allow you to execute a block of code repeatedly based on a
                certain condition. They are fundamental for automating repetitive tasks and iterating over collections
                of data. There are three primary types of loops in Java:</p>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <h5>for Loop:</h5>
                    <p>The for loop is used when you know the number of iterations in advance.
                        It consists of three parts: initialization, condition, and increment (or decrement).
                        The loop continues executing until the condition becomes false.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <h5>while Loop:</h5>
                    <p>The while loop is used when you may not know the number of iterations in advance, and the loop
                        continues executing as long as a specified condition is true.
                        It checks the condition before each iteration.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <h5>do-while Loop:</h5>
                    <p>

                        The do-while loop is similar to the while loop, but it guarantees that the loop body will
                        execute at least once, as it checks the condition after executing the loop body.
                        It is useful when you want to execute the loop body at least once before checking the condition.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
            <hr>
            <p>Loops statements include some of the following concepts</p>
            <h5>break statement</h5>
            <p> Used to exit a loop prematurely, immediately terminating the loop's execution.</p>
            <h5>continue Statement:</h5>
            <p> Skips the current iteration of a loop and continues with the next iteration.</p>
            <h5>Nested Loops: </h5>
            <p>You can have loops inside other loops, allowing for complex looping patterns.</p>
            <h5>Infinite Loops: </h5>
            <p>Be cautious of creating loops that never terminate, as they can lead to program hangs or crashes.</p>
            <h3>Example</h3>
            <div class="code_container">
